068a6-27ae-445a-96ba-5097d8273da7\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_013JNQsBPRTa1EdHoEYNBDeo\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Review 01\\n     2→\\n     3→> Status: addressed\\n     4→> Date: 2026-03-16\\n     5→> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n     6→> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n     7→\\n     8→## Previous Review Status\\n     9→\\n    10→No previous reviews.\\n    11→\\n    12→## New Findings\\n    13→\\n    14→### Critical (Must Fix)\\n    15→\\n    16→- **[cmd/entire/cli/osroot.go] Dead code: `rootReadFile`, `rootWriteFile`, `rootRemove` are unused.** These thin wrappers in the `cli` package delegate to `osroot.ReadFile` etc. but nothing outside the test file calls them. All production code imports `osroot` directly. The linter will flag these as unused (or the tests are testing wrappers nobody calls). Either remove them entirely and update the tests to use `osroot` directly, or remove the file altogether -- the `osroot` package tests already cover the same functionality.\\n    17→\\n    18→- **[cmd/entire/cli/state.go:143,213,480,546] No input validation on `sessionID`/`toolUseID` before constructing filenames.** The `session/state.go` correctly calls `validation.ValidateSessionID()` before all operations, but the pre-prompt and pre-task state functions in `state.go` do not validate their inputs at all. If `sessionID` or `toolUseID` contains a `/`, the filename passed to `os.Root` (e.g., `\\\"pre-prompt-foo/bar.json\\\"`) would create/access a subdirectory within the root -- not a traversal escape, but unexpected behavior. Add `validation.ValidateSessionID(sessionID)` at the top of `CapturePrePromptState`, `LoadPrePromptState`, `CleanupPrePromptState`, and corresponding validation for `toolUseID` in the pre-task functions, or at minimum reject path separators in the ID before constructing the filename.\\n    19→\\n    20→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    21→\\n    22→- **[cmd/entire/cli/state.go:214,547] Misleading nolint comment: `//nolint:wrapcheck // error context in osroot.Remove`.** `osroot.Remove` does NOT add error context -- it returns the raw `root.Remove(name)` error. The nolint is correct to suppress the lint, but the justification is inaccurate. Change to something like `//nolint:wrapcheck // best-effort cleanup, caller adds no context intentionally`.\\n    23→\\n    24→- **[cmd/entire/cli/utils.go:59-91] `openAllowedRoot` resolves `dst` through symlinks but only resolves the parent directory.** The function does `filepath.EvalSymlinks(filepath.Dir(dst))` and then re-joins with `filepath.Base(dst)`. If `dst` itself is a symlink (the final component), this won't resolve it. This is actually fine for security (os.Root handles that at the kernel level), but the comment says \\\"Resolve dst through symlinks so that e.g. /var/folders/... matches /private/var/folders/... on macOS\\\" -- this could be clarified to say it resolves the directory portion only, since the file may not exist yet.\\n    25→\\n    26→- **[cmd/entire/cli/utils.go:79-83] `openAllowedRoot` uses `filepath.Rel` + prefix check instead of `paths.IsSubpath`.** The function has a comment \\\"This is the same logic as paths.IsSubpath but avoids a redundant filepath.Rel call since we already have rel.\\\" This is a reasonable optimization, but it duplicates the traversal check logic. If `IsSubpath` is ever updated (e.g., to handle edge cases), this copy would get out of sync. Consider either calling `paths.IsSubpath(dir, resolvedDst)` and accepting the double `filepath.Rel` call (it is cheap), or extracting the core logic into a helper like `paths.IsSubpathRel(rel string) bool` that both can use.\\n    27→\\n    28→- **[cmd/entire/cli/state.go:385-390,550-558] `prePromptStateFile` and `preTaskStateFile` are now only used by tests.** Production code has been refactored to construct filenames inline. These functions should either be removed (updating the tests to construct paths differently) or kept explicitly for test use. As-is, they are nearly dead code. If kept, consider annotating them or moving them to a `_test.go` file.\\n    29→\\n    30→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n    31→\\n    32→- **[cmd/entire/cli/metadata.go:43,59,81] Consider scoping metadata os.Root to the repo worktree root instead of taskMetadataDir.** The requirements say \\\"Should use os.Root scoped to the repo worktree root for reads and writes.\\\" Currently, each function opens `os.Root` at `taskMetadataDir` (a deeply nested path like `.entire/metadata/<sessionID>/tasks/<toolUseID>/`). This is safe but provides a narrow scope -- the main threat model is about preventing escape from the repo root, not from within metadata subdirectories. Using the repo root as the `os.Root` scope (with relative paths from there) would match the requirements more closely, though the current approach is arguably more restrictive and equally safe.\\n    33→\\n    34→- **[cmd/entire/cli/osroot/osroot.go] Consider adding `WriteFile` sync/flush before close.** The current `WriteFile` does `f.Write(data)` then `defer f.Close()`. For durability (especially on the session state atomic-write path), consider calling `f.Sync()` before close. This is not critical -- the atomic rename in `session/state.go` provides crash safety -- but could prevent partial writes if the system crashes between write and close.\\n    35→\\n    36→- **[cmd/entire/cli/session/state.go:377-389] `Clear` falls back to `os.Remove` if `os.OpenRoot` fails.** This silently degrades security. Consider logging a warning when falling back, or simply returning the error instead of silently degrading. The fallback means that if the state directory has a permissions issue, the function silently uses the non-os.Root path.\\n    37→\\n    38→- **[cmd/entire/cli/paths/paths.go:127-137] `IsSubpath` documents \\\"traversal-resistant\\\" but only provides lexical checking.** The function is purely lexical (filepath.Rel cleans paths) -- it does NOT prevent TOCTOU symlink races. This is fine for its use cases (filtering git status output), but the docstring could clarify that it is a lexical check, distinct from the kernel-level protection provided by os.Root.\\n    39→\\n    40→### Praise\\n    41→\\n    42→- Clean extraction of `osroot` package with well-documented API surface. The package clearly documents which operations `os.Root` supports vs. not, and the tests cover traversal attacks, symlinks, and normal operations thoroughly.\\n    43→- Good defense-in-depth approach in `manual_commit_rewind.go` -- even though paths come from git tree objects (trusted), the os.Root scoping adds a safety net.\\n    44→- The `IsSubpath` utility in `paths/paths.go` is a solid abstraction that replaces ad-hoc prefix checks, with thorough test coverage including traversal attack cases.\\n    45→- Refactoring `copyFile` to use `openAllowedRoot` with actual `os.Root` handles (instead of the previous lexical `validateCopyDst`) is a meaningful security improvement -- kernel-enforced containment vs. TOCTOU-vulnerable string checks.\\n    46→- The `allowedRootDirs` / `appendResolved` helpers clean up the symlink resolution logic nicely.\\n    47→\\n    48→## Summary\\n    49→\\n    50→- **Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n    51→- **Key concerns:**\\n    52→  1. Dead code in `cmd/entire/cli/osroot.go` -- the `rootReadFile`/`rootWriteFile`/`rootRemove` wrappers and their tests duplicate the `osroot` package and are unused by production code. This will likely fail linting.\\n    53→  2. Missing input validation in `state.go` pre-prompt/pre-task functions -- `sessionID` and `toolUseID` are not validated before being interpolated into filenames. While os.Root prevents directory escape, path separators in the ID would create unexpected subdirectory structures.\\n    54→- **Estimated effort to address feedback:** 30-60 minutes. The dead code removal is straightforward, and adding validation calls is a few lines per function.\\n    55→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"71c0d92e-492c-4951-88f1-db4f6ea95233\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T15:15:53.067Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"ac6da6798614ec01b\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01U3hCNWmqYKGTQp6Hta99Lp\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01E9AoJBrDR3oHDZBNUBozXq\",\"uuid\":\"6c736f5e-fcee-4889-8813-e602b41006f3\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T15:15:53.943Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"cf90776f-5d3e-48d9-8b85-54e092326a6b\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/os-root-traversal-resistant\",\"slug\":\"sprightly-finding-rivest\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"6c736f5e-fcee-4889-8813-e602b41006f3\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T15:15:53.969Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01P9G8m6CaCJedv5CVHXKBa2\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01PegKn7oNtp9gsCpLPgT7QK\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/paths/paths.go\",\"limit\":50,\"offset\":100},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1699,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":71053,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":1699,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":25,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ6ykUWFx4rfv41jc1dL4\",\"uuid\":\"b34b2a6a-9f34-41af-9827-d4d4df4589c4\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"ac6da6798614ec01b\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01U3hCNWmqYKGTQp6Hta99Lp\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01E9AoJBrDR3oHDZBNUBozXq\",\"uuid\":\"63b3842f-e72d-424d-8871-c0ec58bca63b\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T15:15:53.969Z\",\